		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27436571">There are some strong contenders for this one, but I have to go with Yasaburou from Uchouten Kazoku. Not only does he breathe the heart and soul of the work's drama, he also drives the comedy and all of his private conversations as he roams around the city. Several of the characters are closeted people by nature (Akadama-sensei, for instance), and Yasaburou makes each of them feel comfortable enough to open up. Most of all, he remains strongly identifiable and human, being flawed enough to be personable while with distinguishable traits to keep him as one to continuously root for. His cheeky remarks are clever and fun, oftentimes incorporating the fantastical elements of the work/setting into his jokes instead of relying only on verbal cues.<br />
<br />
He's what keeps the story intact, and is primarily what makes it so thoroughly enjoyable. I've also found his characterization solid since the premiere, and he grows subtly but assuredly as the conflict with the Ebisugawa family begins to close. His relationships with each of his family as the middle brother feels authentic—from younger brother to older, or even the mother or father. It's played softly so that it doesn't feel too harsh as drama can tend to be. I'm also quite fond of the way Uchouten Kazoku portrays his ambiguous feelings of love, friendship, and/or infatuation with Benten (and later on, Kaisei).</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
