		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27516805">Rui Ninomiya<br />
<br />
Rui embodies a real human, yet compromising attempt at improving the world. He is the real star of Gatchaman Crowds. It is hard to discuss him without also mentioning his foils - Hajime, the more traditional "main character" of the show, has similar ambitions but is optimistic to a fault and incredibly naive. While it is fun to root for her, she has the usual faults of a protagonist in shows like this; she's too trusting, uses her instincts to make decisions too often, almost has no concept of selfishness, and it is overall just not feasible to actually act like she does and expect things to go right. Then there's Berg-Katze, the polar opposite of Hajime. He is nihilistic, trusts no one while blaming selfishness, and deceives people constantly. They are both pretty flat and not very good role models. Rui exists between them, understanding that people can be good but aren't always, can be bad but aren't always. People act the way they do because they weigh the consequences of actions and choose to do what seems like the best action in their own self interest, which can include helping other people simply because that makes people feel good. So he uses that. He uses GALAX to give people an incentive to help other people, giving them both the immediate satisfaction of earning points and such, as well as the reward that comes later when their efforts are noticed by others and a feeling of community is created. He's practical, intelligent, and interesting.<br />
<br />
Close but no cigar:<br />
Hachiman Hikigaya<br />
- An edgy teenager that, for once, isn't played as inherently smarter or more "right" than his peers, but not always wrong either. He also has real flaws but you are totally able to root for him sometimes anyway.<br />
Yugo Hachiken<br />
- Sort of like Hachiman, but for a different archetype. The indecisive, pushover main character, but not without his own moments of real effort and friendliness that makes him more like an actual person than a personality-less self insert protagonist.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by NavyCherub, 01-22-14, 10:53 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
That one may smile, and smile, and be a villain.&quot;</div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
